To add a selection for a speech to text model to the existing code, you'll want to follow a similar pattern to the other settings changes. Here's how you can do it:

1. **Assumption:** Assuming that there's a list of speech to text models similar to the `models` prop for other models, you will need to have a similar array for speech to text models. For demonstration, I'll assume this data is passed as a prop called `speechModels`.
2. **Add a Handler Function:** You'll need a function to handle changes to the speech to text model selection.
3. **Add the Selection in the UI:** You'll introduce a new `<select>` element for the speech to text model, populated with options based on the `speechModels` prop.

Here is the modified version of your component, focusing only on the addition of the speech to text model selection:

```javascript
import React from "react";
import PropTypes from "prop-types";
import { useTranslation } from "react-i18next";

import { userShape } from "../../../model/userPropType";
import "./GeneralTab.scss";

const GeneralTab = ({ user, setUser, models, speechModels }) => { // Assume speechModels is passed as a prop
  const { t } = useTranslation();

  const handleModelChange = (e) => {
    setUser((prevSettings) => ({
      ...prevSettings,
      settings: {
        ...prevSettings.settings,
        model: e.target.value,
      },
    }));
  };

  // Existing handlers...

  const handleSpeechModelChange = (e) => {
    setUser((prevSettings) => ({
      ...prevSettings,
      settings: {
        ...prevSettings.settings,
        speechModel: e.target.value, // Add or update speechModel in settings
      },
    }));
  };

  const options = models.map((model) => (
    <option key={model.name} value={model.name}>
      {model.name}
    </option>
  ));

  const speechOptions = speechModels.map((model) => ( // Create options for speechModels
    <option key={model.name} value={model.name}>
      {model.name}
    </option>
  ));

  return (
    <div className="general-tab">
      <label>
        {t('model_title')}:
        <select value={user.settings.model} onChange={handleModelChange}>
          {options}
        </select>
      </label>

      {/* Existing UI elements... */}

      <label> {/* Add a new label and select for speech to text model */}
        {t('speech_model_title')}:
        <select value={user.settings.speechModel} onChange={handleSpeechModelChange}>
          {speechOptions}
        </select>
      </label>
    </div>
  );
};

GeneralTab.propTypes = {
  user: userShape.isRequired,
  setUser: PropTypes.func.isRequired,
  models: PropTypes.arrayOf(
    PropTypes.shape({
      name: PropTypes.string.isRequired,
    })
  ).isRequired,
  speechModels: PropTypes.arrayOf( // Expect speechModels prop similar to models
    PropTypes.shape({
      name: PropTypes.string.isRequired,
    })
  ).isRequired,
};

export default GeneralTab;
```

**Note:** This assumes you have a `speechModels` prop similar to `models` and that your user settings object in the state has a field for `speechModel` to hold the selected speech to text model. Adjust the names and structure according to your actual data and state management.

