```java
public class BubbleSort {

    void bubbleSort(int arr[]) {
        int n = arr.length;
        for (int i = 0; i < n-1; i++) {
            for (int j = 0; j < n-i-1; j++) {
                if (arr[j] > arr[j+1]) {
                    // swap arr[j+1] and arr[j]
                    int temp = arr[j];
                    arr[j] = arr[j+1];
                    arr[j+1] = temp;
                }
            }
        }
    }

    // Method to print the elements of an array
    void printArray(int arr[]) {
        int n = arr.length;
        for (int i=0; i<n; ++i)
            System.out.print(arr[i] + " ");
        System.out.println();
    }

    // Driver method to test above
    public static void main(String args[]) {
        BubbleSort ob = new BubbleSort();
        int arr[] = {64, 34, 25, 12, 22, 11, 90};
        ob.bubbleSort(arr);
        System.out.println("Sorted array");
        ob.printArray(arr);
    }
}
```

This code defines a `BubbleSort` class with a `bubbleSort` method that sorts an array of integers. The `printArray` method is used to print the array after sorting. The `main` method creates an instance of `BubbleSort`, initializes an array of integers, and then uses the `bubbleSort` method to sort the array. Finally, it prints the sorted array.

Creating a visual display of the sorting process in a console-based Java program is somewhat limited, but you can certainly print the array at each step to see how the elements are being sorted. For a more sophisticated visual representation, you would typically use a GUI framework like JavaFX or Swing, but that's quite complex and beyond the scope of a simple example. 

Here's a modified version of the Bubble Sort program that prints the array at each step of the sorting process:

```java
public class BubbleSort {

    void bubbleSort(int arr[]) {
        int n = arr.length;
        for (int i = 0; i < n-1; i++) {
            for (int j = 0; j < n-i-1; j++) {
                if (arr[j] > arr[j+1]) {
                    // swap arr[j+1] and arr[j]
                    int temp = arr[j];
                    arr[j] = arr[j+1];
                    arr[j+1] = temp;
                }
                printArray(arr); // Print array after each swap
            }
        }
    }

    // Method to print the elements of an array
    void printArray(int arr[]) {
        for (int i : arr)
            System.out.print(i + " ");
        System.out.println();
    }

    // Driver method to test above
    public static void main(String args[]) {
        BubbleSort ob = new BubbleSort();
        int arr[] = {64, 34, 25, 12, 22, 11, 90};
        System.out.println("Original array: ");
        ob.printArray(arr);
        System.out.println("\nSorting steps: ");
        ob.bubbleSort(arr);
        System.out.println("\nSorted array: ");
        ob.printArray(arr);
    }
}
```

In this version, the `bubbleSort` method prints the array after each swap, allowing you to see how the elements are moved around in each iteration. This will help you visualize the sorting process in the console. Remember that this will result in a large number of outputs, especially for large arrays.

